file=Product/spec/custom/prd-discipline/SKILL.md · h=name: prd-discipline\ntype: custom\nstatus: built from scratch\nfulfills_catalog_entry: vyon-prd-template (prefix stripped; per-product specifics moved to operator product profiles)\nassigned_agent: spec (Product / Product Manager, department leader)\nportable: true\ndate_added: 2026-07-10\n · in:=The house standard for what a PRD is: problem, evidence, scope, explicit out-of-scope, and acceptance criteria written to be testable at quinn's gate. The Evidence Gate's document-shaped enforcement point.\n · p:=PRDs without evidence are feature requests in formalwear; PRDs without out-of-scope sections grow silently; criteria quinn can't test are wishes. This skill makes each failure structurally impossible.\n · wu:=- Any feature/product idea survives opportunity-assessment and needs specification.\n- An existing PRD is amended (same discipline, versioned).\n- Engineering bounces criteria as untestable (repair loop).\n · st:/ Protocol=Every PRD, same order: (1) PROBLEM — whose, observed where; (2) EVIDENCE — citations to ux repo entries, metric reads, or loom verdicts (the Evidence Gate: no citations, no PRD); (3) PROPOSED SCOPE — smallest coherent slice; (4) OUT-OF-SCOPE — explicit, named, with the "not yet vs not ever" tag; (5) SUCCESS METRIC — the ONE metric (from metric's spec, by its versioned definition) this ships to move, with target `<FILL_IN per PRD>`; (6) ACCEPTANCE CRITERIA — testable statements per acceptance-criteria-handoff's standard; (7) RISKS + rollback stance.\n · i:=1. Evidence citations are real references (repo entry IDs, scorecard lines, experiment registry IDs) — "users want this" uncited bounces at intake.\n2. The success metric uses metric's versioned definition by name — a PRD inventing its own "activation" is a metrics-governance violation.\n3. Out-of-scope is written before scope review — it's the negotiation surface, not an afterthought.\n4. Amendments version the PRD (dated changelog in the doc); the shipped-against version is frozen at handoff.\n5. A PRD whose evidence is only opinion-level (validation ladder 1–2, per loom's shared ladder) must say so and route through loom for a cheap falsifying test before Engineering sees it — unless the operator explicitly overrides (recorded).\n · of:=The 7-section PRD; amendment changelogs; bounce notices citing the failed section.\n · pr:=- No evidence, no PRD; no out-of-scope, no scope; no testable criteria, no handoff.\n- One success metric — a PRD that moves "several things" moves nothing accountably.\n- Written to be falsified: a PRD that can't fail its metric read is decoration.\n · f:=Genuinely evidence-free but operator-mandated ("strategic bet")? The PRD says `EVIDENCE: operator directive <ref>, validation ladder L1` honestly — the gate records the exception rather than laundering it.\n · b:with Other Skills=- opportunity-assessment precedes (whether to spec at all); backlog-rules sequences; acceptance-criteria-handoff delivers.\n- metric owns metric definitions; ux/loom own the evidence kinds; vista owns roadmap placement.\n